name: The Eugene Register-Guard
articlebody:
Spring vacation can be frustrating in Oregon, with rain at the coast and snow on mountain hiking trails. Why not escape to San Francisco?
In fact the Gold Rush city has excellent March hiking, and there's a backdoor route for Oregonians who have driven down to avoid the rain. When our tulips are still just poking up through the rain-matted sod, the summer flowers in San Francisco are already going full blast, with entire hedges of geraniums blooming beneath palm trees.
The trick is to avoid the tourist crowds in the hectic eastern half of San Francisco. Yes, that busier, pricier side of the city has all the big-name attractions: Fisherman's Wharf, Chinatown and cable cars. But let me recommend a different San Francisco. Sneak into the quieter, west side of town via the Golden Gate Bridge.
My wife and I chose an Airbnb in Mill Valley, just a 10-minute drive north of San Francisco over the Golden Gate. A room in Mill Valley costs half as much as in San Francisco, and is likely to be in an actual house with parking, a yard and a hot tub.
Mill Valley is a New Age hangout for wealthy hippies. When we told our hostess Barbara that we were from Oregon, she responded, "Too cool!" Buddha statues began in her front yard and followed us throughout the house. Buddhas lounged before her fireplace and watched us from beside a green lava lamp. The lava lamp was the brightest light in a living room full of candles, mirrors, rugs and bamboo.
Barbara told us she had once been a competitive triathlon athlete but now struggles to make ends meet by appraising properties, leading fitness classes and renting out a bedroom to visitors. She admitted that she has been to Oregon three times for Cycle Oregon tours -- not for the bicycling, but rather in the hopes of meeting a single, active Oregon lawyer in the 55-75 range (not a doctor; she had tried that already) who could supplement her income.
Driving into San Francisco over the Golden Gate Bridge is not terrifying if you wait until 9:30 a.m., after the morning commute. There is an $8 toll in this direction, but traffic isn't stopped to collect it. Instead your license plate is photographed and you're sent a bill. Coming back is free.
Beyond the bridge take the first exit and keep straight for two miles to Golden Gate Park. This gigantic natural preserve was created out of sand dunes and scrub, beginning in the 1880s. There's lots to do here -- rent paddleboats, visit museums -- but I recommend starting at the Botanical Garden. Here you'll find Oregon's summer wildflowers already doing fine in March -- along with weird plants from South Africa, New Zealand and Tibet.
My second suggestion in west San Francisco is the Legion of Honor Museum. There are many other art museums in the Bay Area, but this is the goofiest and most random. Within a pompous classical temple on a hill overlooking the Golden Gate you'll find Egyptian mummies, Rodin sculptures, a French room of gold and an upscale cafe in an olive grove.
My third suggestion is the Lands End Lookout, a National Park Service visitor center overlooking the Pacific where Geary Avenue meets El Camino Del Mar. Here you'll find easy parking and a visitor center with views, history displays and friendly rangers. A one-mile walking loop south visits the weird beachfront ruins of the Sutro Baths (a former swim hall), the Cliff House restaurant (a former clifftop castle and amusement park) and Ocean Beach (with surfers and two completely incongruous Dutch windmills).
A one-mile walking loop north of the Lands End Lookout follows an old railroad grade to viewpoints of the Golden Gate, rocky islands, shipwrecks and windswept forests of scenic Monterey cypresses.
From Lands End drive Camino Del Mar and its continuation, Lincoln Boulevard, northeast across Highway 101 to the shore of San Francisco Bay. At the far end of the Presidio (an old military outpost), park at the Palace of Fine Arts. You will see the dome of this classical monstrosity from miles away. Ginormous concrete Corinthian columns line the walking path to a completely free -- and completely ridiculous -- pseudo Greek/Roman temple to art, as understood by the heirs of San Francisco's Gold Rush wealth.
Then, from the same parking spot, cross at a stoplight to a marina on the bay. Walk out past the yachts to a jetty. There are no signs, but continue to the jetty's end to find the Wave Organ, an interactive art project honoring the physicist Frank Oppenheimer. At high tide waves gurgle into tubes that bring their "music" to worm-shaped ear pieces along the jetty's end. Stone steps, benches and wind-sheltered alcoves have been built here with carved granite blocks salvaged from an abandoned cemetery. Does it get weirder and wilder than this in San Francisco?
Yes! At the Wave Organ the evening sun sinks into the Golden Gate, casting in pink the skyscrapers of the city and the derelict cell blocks on Alcatraz Island. Across the bay, picture windows of homes in Berkeley flash orange, reflecting the setting sun. Grebes dive, seals peer out from the waves and herons stalk the sandy shallows, eyeing you suspiciously.
The little sailboats that darted out after work begin tacking back to the marina. Gigantic container ships honk for tugs to guide them into the bay. Boeing 747s bank overhead, setting out on overnight flights across the Pacific. The ellipsoid Salesforce Tower, the tallest building in San Francisco, catches the last rays of the sun.
Unlike Fisherman's Wharf, there are no restaurants here, and no crowds. Bring your own picnic for the sunset. And then, after the evening commuter traffic over the Golden Gate Bridge eases, drive north in the twilight to Mill Valley.
If you're staying on the north side of the Golden Gate, the most popular hiking destination in the area will be Muir Woods, a national monument that sees 1.4 million visitors a year. You can't just show up here and expect to hike. It's the closest redwood grove to San Francisco and now requires advance parking permits, so plan ahead.
Most of the redwoods on Mount Tamalpais, the iconic Marin County peak visible throughout the Bay, were cut following the Gold Rush. Logging railroads extended to the summit but had trouble reaching one deep valley on the southwest flank. In the 1890s the Bohemian Society -- a proto-hippie elite of poets, artists and drunks -- held Bacchanalian picnics here with a 30-foot plaster statue of Buddha. When logging threatened the valley in 1906, John Muir spurred a local landowner to save the forest with his poem, "Any Fool Can Kill a Tree."
Today Muir Woods is a one-square-mile national monument with a grove of 10-foot-diameter redwoods. To visit, you have to buy a parking reservation at gomuirwoods.com, paying $8.50 and choosing a half-hour arrival time slot. This will give your phone a barcode to show the parking lot attendants. If you show up without this barcode you're out of luck, because there is no cell phone or internet service at the trailhead. In addition to the parking fee, expect an admission of $15 per adult.
Most tourists simply stroll a boardwalk up along a creek 0.8 mile amid the big trees. To escape the crowds, however, continue into the state parklands beyond. Of the many possible loops, the one up Fern Creek has the best redwoods and water features, and only adds a mile or two.
Muir Woods has a gift shop with a cafe, but it's better to hold out a bit for lunch. Drive curvy, scenic Highway 1 north to the Muir Beach Overlook, where World War II bunkers overhang sea cliffs with views from the Golden Gate to the Farallon Islands. Then continue on Highway 1 to the funky beach village of Stinson Beach. Here the Parkside Cafe has $6 homemade bread with the best-ever homemade pesto, using whole pinyon pine nuts.
Admittedly, there's a day or two of driving between Oregon and San Francisco, but if you've got a week for spring vacation -- and if you sneak into the quiet western side of the city -- it's a great way to get a jump on the adventures of summer.
